{"Title": "The use of short and wide x-ray pulses for time-of-flight x-ray Compton Scatter Imaging in cargo security", "Year": 2015, "Source": "Proc SPIE Int Soc Opt Eng", "Volume": "9456", "Issue": null, "Art.No": null, "PageStart": null, "PageEnd": null, "CitedBy": 0, "DOI": "10.1117/12.2176832", "Link": "https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&scp=84948807982&origin=inward", "Abstract": "\u00a9 COPYRIGHT SPIE. Downloading of the abstract is permitted for personal use only.Using a short pulse width x-ray source and measuring the time-of-flight of photons that scatter from an object under inspection allows for the point of interaction to be determined, and a profile of the object to be sampled along the path of the beam. A three dimensional image can be formed by interrogating the entire object. Using high energy x rays enables the inspection of cargo containers with steel walls, in the search for concealed items. A longer pulse width x-ray source can also be used with deconvolution techniques to determine the points of interaction. We present time-of-flight results from both short (picosecond) width and long (hundreds of nanoseconds) width x-ray sources, and show that the position of scatter can be localised with a resolution of 2 ns, equivalent to 30 cm, for a 3 cm thick plastic test object.", "AuthorKeywords": null, "IndexKeywords": ["Cargo containers", "Cargo security", "Compton scatter imaging", "Deconvolution techniques", "High energy X ray", "Short pulse width", "Three dimensional images", "Time of flight", "Xray imaging"], "DocumentType": "Conference Proceeding", "PublicationStage": null, "OpenAccess": 0, "EID": "2-s2.0-84948807982", "SubjectAreas": [["Electronic, Optical and Magnetic Materials", "MATE", "2504"], ["Condensed Matter Physics", "PHYS", "3104"], ["Computer Science Applications", "COMP", "1706"], ["Applied Mathematics", "MATH", "2604"], ["Electrical and Electronic Engineering", "ENGI", "2208"]], "AuthorData": {"56429044500": 